-- pd.package: FTD lato package
name: fastn-community.github.io/lato-font

This FTD font `lato` package is for your ftd web projects. To Use this
lato inside `FTD` project follow below instructions.

-- ds.h3: How to use lato?

-- ds.code: Add this to your FASTN.ftd
lang: ftd

\-- fastn.dependency: fastn-community.github.io/lato-font

-- ds.markdown: 

After adding lato dependency inside you `FASTN.ftd` file, You need to add
lato assets and import it inside you `ftd` file where you are using this
font for your custom font types. To include lato into your `ftd` file
follow below instructions.

-- ds.code:
lang: ftd

\-- import: fastn-community.github.io/lato-font/assets as lato-assets


-- ds.h3: How to create a custom lato type? 

-- ds.markdown: 

How to use `ftd.type` to create a custom font `types` using lato? 

We don't recommend creating custom types. We recommend to use 
our [lato-typography](https://fastn-community.github.io/lato-typography)

If you're using [lato-typography](https://fastn-community.github.io/lato-typography) 
and still your designer has introduced new font size which is not included or 
part of our [lato-typography](https://fastn-community.github.io/lato-typography) 
then only define custom types. 

We hope you shouldn't need to define a custom type.

Below is an example of creating a custom `ftd.type` using lato.

-- ds.rendered:

-- ds.rendered.input:

\-- ftd.type lato-size-12-desktop:
size.px: 12
weight: 400
font-family: $lato-assets.fonts.Lato


\-- ftd.type lato-size-12-mobile:
size.px: 12
weight: 400
font-family: $lato-assets.fonts.Lato

\-- ftd.responsive-type lato-size-12-400:
desktop: $lato-size-12-desktop
mobile: $lato-size-12-mobile

-- ds.rendered.output:

-- ftd.text: 
role: $lato-size-12-400
color: $inherited.colors.text-strong

